    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1926-07-17T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1926-07-17T00:00:00-05:00" n="51"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d51">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">860i.855/1</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Estonian Chargé</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Mutt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Acting Chief of the Division of Eastern
                        European Affairs</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Kelley</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">New York</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1926-07-17">
                            <hi rend="italic">July 17, 1926</hi>
                        </date>.<lb/>[Received July 19.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Kelley</hi>: At the time of conclusion of
                    Commercial Treaty between the United States of America and Esthonia<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d51fn1">Treaty of Friendship, Commerce and Consular Rights between
                        the United States and Estonia, signed Dec. 23, 1925, <ref
                            target="frus1925v02#pg_70">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1925, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>, p. 70</ref>.</note> the question of mutual
                    recognition of ships measurement certificates was also up. In the conference had
                    between you, the Esthonian Minister A. Piip and Mr. C. M. Barnes<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d51fn2">Assistant to the Solicitor.</note> on November 11, 1925 it
                    was decided not to make this by the Commercial Treaty but by special exchange of
                    notes or by special declarations. Lately I received from the Minister of Foreign
                    Affairs of Esthonia English translation of the Esthonian ships measurement
                    certificates with request to forward the enclosed three copies of Regulations
                    for tonnage measurement of ships to Mr. C. M. Barnes and to take further steps
                    toward the recognition. I might say that the Esthonian regulations correspond to
                    those of British in all its technical requirements.</p>
                <p>Very sincerely yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">V. Mutt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
